{{Infobox saint |name=Abai |birth_date= |death_date=363<ref>{{cite book | title = The Scattered Pearls : a History of Syriac Literature and Sciences | author = Ignatius Aphram I. Barsoum (Ighnāṭyūs Afrām I), Patriarch of Antioch | page = 164 | publisher = Gorgias Press LLC | location = New Jersey | isbn = 1-931956-04-9 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=0f-eB_KK7fAC&pg=PA164&lpg=PA164&dq=abai+martyr#v=onepage&q=abai%20martyr&f=false | accessdate = 9 October 2012 | quote = ...Saba the youth and his companion Abai in 363... | year = 2003}}</ref><ref>Death year is listed differently in two references – 363 in ''The Scattered Pearls'' and 460 in ''Kalendarium''. His death year is listed as 363 in this article because that date corresponds to the reign of [[Shapur II]], King of the Persian Sassanid Empire from 309 to 379.</ref> |feast_day=October 1 |venerated_in=Syriac Orthodox Church |image= |imagesize= |caption= |birth_place= |death_place= |titles= |beatified_date= |beatified_place= |beatified_by= |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |patronage= |major_shrine= |suppressed_date= |issues= }}
'''Abai''' was a [[martyr]] in Syria. He was killed during the reign of [[Shapur II]]. He is a [[saint]] in the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and his feast day is October 1.<ref>{{cite book | title = Calendar of Historical Events, Births, Holidays and Observances | publisher = MobileReference | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=t4YZUcjx6poC&pg=PT2142&lpg=PT2142&dq=abai+martyr | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781605011097}}</ref> He is included in ''[[Kalendarium Manuale Utriusque Ecclesiae Orientalis et Occidentalis]]''.<ref>{{cite book | title = Kalendarium manuale utriusque ecclesiae orientalis et occidentalis | volume=2 | first = Nicolaus | last = Nilles | year = 1897 | language = Latin | page = 379 | quote = S. Abai, m. in Perside, 460.}}</ref> He had been killed by his father Adorpirozgerd who later became a Christian. He was killed together with other 5000 martyrs including his mother Astina (Hwarta). He was mentioned in the legend of Sābā Pirgushnasp, a child martyr, who had been a son of the governor of Beth ʿArabaye and had been killed under the [[Shapur II]]. Approximately the years of his life are 335-385 AD.<ref>[http://syriaca.org/person/1093/ Syriac Biographical Dictionary, Abai, Syriac Not Available (sometime between 335 - 385)] Retrieved on 6 Feb 2018</ref>
Abai is not to be confused with the Syriac saint [[Abhai (saint)|Abhai]].
