{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} [[File:San Nicolò dei Mendicoli (Venice) ceiling.jpg|thumb|upright 1.3|Ceiling of [[San Nicolò dei Mendicoli]] Venice]] [[File:Biography of Francesco Montemezzano by Claudio Ridolfi.png|thumb|right|Biography of Francesco Montemezzano by Ridolfi]] '''Francesco Montemezzano''' or '''Monte Mezzano''' ([[Verona]] 1555–after 1602) was an [[Italian people|Italian]] painter of the late-[[Renaissance art|Renaissance]] or [[Mannerism|Mannerist]] period.
He was born near [[Verona]], and appears to have been a follower, if not a pupil, of [[Paolo Veronese]].<ref>[http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/437146 Metropolitan Museum Collections].</ref> He was active both in Venice and the mainland, painting mainly sacred subjects.<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/francesco-montemezzano_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ Enciclopedia Treccani], Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani - Volume 76 (2012), entry by Giorgio Tagliaferro</ref>
He completed some of the panels for the church of [[San Nicolo dei Mendicoli, Venice|San Nicolò dei Mendicoli]]. [[Claudio Ridolfi|Ridolfi]] in a short biography notes that Francesco ''gave himself excessively to the pleasures of love, fell in love with expensive objects'' and this led to an early death by poisoning.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/lemaravigliedell02rido#page/334/mode/2up Le Maraviglie dell'arte: overo le vite de gl'illustri pittori Veneti], Volume 2, By Carlo Ridolfi, 1648, page 334.</ref>
==Media== He was featured in the BBC One television programme ''[[Fake or Fortune?]]'' on 19 July 2015, in which a painting in an English church, [[St John the Baptist's Church, Tunstall]], Lancashire, was verified as being by the artist.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b063cy0z/fake-or-fortune-series-4-3-a-mystery-old-master</ref>
