'''Jakob Nufer''' was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] pig-gelder who, around [[1500 in science|1500]], reportedly performed the first successful [[Caesarean section]] in history in which the mother (his wife) survived.<ref>{{cite book|last=Conner|first=Clifford D.|title=A People's History of Science|publisher=Nation Books|location=New York|year=2005|isbn=1-56025-748-2|pages=312}}</ref>
His wife allegedly bore five more children, including twins, and the baby delivered by Caesarean section purportedly lived to the age of 77.<ref>{{cite book|last=Henry|first=John|editor=Stephen Pumphrey |editor2=Paolo L. Rossi |editor3=Maurice Slawinski|chapter=Doctors and Healers: Popular Culture and the Medical Profession|title=Science, Culture, and Popular Belief in Renaissance Europe|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|location=New York|year=1991|isbn=0-7190-2925-2|pages=197}}</ref>
However, the story was not recorded until 1582 and many historians question its accuracy.<ref>Sewell, Jane Eliot. [https://www.nlm.nih.gov/hmd/pdf/cesarean.pdf National Library on Medicine], "Cesarean Section: A Brief History" (1993)</ref>
