'''Steven Hayden Pollock''' was a [[mycologist]] who studied [[psychoactive mushrooms]] and published many articles on the potential of mushrooms to treat illness and improve quality of life.<ref name="LibertyCapsPsychotherapeuticPotential">{{cite journal|last1=Pollock|first1=Steven Hayden|title=Liberty Caps: recreational hallucinogenic mushrooms|journal=Drug and Alcohol Dependence|date=October 1976|volume=1|issue=6|pages=445–447|doi=10.1016/0376-8716(76)90010-7}}</ref><ref name="PsilocybinMushroomPandemic">{{cite journal|last1=Pollock|first1=Steven Hayden|title=The Psilocybin Mushroom Pandemic|journal=Journal of Psychedelic Drugs|date=17 January 2012|volume=7|issue=1|pages=73–84|doi=10.1080/02791072.1975.10472640}}</ref>{{rp|81}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pollock|first1=Steven Hayden|title=Psilocybian Mycetismus With Special Reference To Panaeolus|journal=Journal of Psychedelic Drugs|date=17 January 2012|volume=8|issue=1|pages=43–57|doi=10.1080/02791072.1976.10472007}}</ref>{{rp|55}}
==Life and career== Pollock and Gary Lincoff found an entirely new species, and named it ''[[Psilocybe tampanensis]]'', in [[Tampa, FL]], September 3, 1977 while the Second International Mycological Congress was happening, Pollock was so excited he said they discovered the [[philosopher’s stone]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Steven Hayden Pollock|author2=Gastón Guzmán|author-link2=Gastón Guzmán|title=A new bluing species of Psilocybe from Florida, U.S.A.|journal=Mycotaxon|date=July–September 1978|volume=7|issue=2|pages=373–376|url=http://www.mykoweb.com/systematics/journals/Mycotaxon/Mycotaxon%20v007n2.pdf|accessdate=2 June 2017|language=en|issn=0093-4666}}</ref><ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|3–4}}
He wrote the Magic Mushroom Cultivation book in 1977, it contained his research on several ways to cultivate magic mushrooms,<ref name="MagicMushroomCultivation">{{cite book|last1=H. Pollock|first1=Steven|title=Magic Mushroom Cultivation|date=1977|publisher=Herbal Medicine Research Foundation|location=San Antonio|isbn=9780930074012|language=en}}</ref> including the cultivation in brown rice that was later demonstrated to produce mushrooms of high [[psilocybin]] content.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|6}}
Pollock isolated a strain of ''P. tampanensis'' that produced [[sclerotia]] of a size much bigger than known before. This discovery enabled a means of using psilocybin in places where magic mushrooms are illegal, such as after the magic mushroom ban in Amsterdam on December 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Truffle takes over from the magic mushroom|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2011/12/truffle_takes_over_from_the_ma/|accessdate=3 June 2017|work=DutchNews.nl|date=1 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amsterdam tourists mad about truffle trips|url=https://www.rnw.org/archive/amsterdam-tourists-mad-about-truffle-trips|website=RNW Media|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|6,16}}
Pollock envisioned creating the first legal medical mushroom research laboratory and estimated he would need about 2 million dollars to set it up.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|6–8}} Together with another mushroom lover, Michael Forbes, they founded a company called Hidden Creek in 1979 to sell ''P. tampanensis'' [[sclerotium]] by mail; they advertised in the monthly magazine [[High Times]], and became the largest magic mushroom vendor in the world within the same year.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|6}}
He sold mushrooms, prescriptions, and planted an acre of [[cannabis]] to get the funds he needed to his research. He traveled to the Amazon and Mexico to study psychoactive mushrooms and discovered 3 species in 1979: ''[[Psilocybe armandii]]'', ''[[Psilocybe wassoniorum]]'', and ''[[Psilocybe schultesii]]''.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|7–8}} In 1980, because of his high volume of illegal prescription writing, the state pharmacy board alerted employees about his practice. As a work-around Pollock bought his own pharmacy to supply his customers.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|8}}
==Death== Pollock worked 7 days a week; on a Saturday at 7 PM he arranged with his girlfriend Mitzi by phone to meet for dinner, but he had a last patient scheduled to come that night. Mitzi called him several times through the night, but he did not answer. Worried, she ran to his office at 11 PM and found the house ransacked. Pollock was in the corner beside the front door, shot dead in the forehead.
The police found 1,753 jars of growing psychoactive mushrooms in his greenhouse that were dumped and burned by San Antonio Narcotics Force.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|10–12}} Gary Davis, Pollock's friend, got a tape of two people talking about Pollock's murder, but kept it in the fear someone would kill him.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|13}}
In 1983, detective Anton Michalec found three suspects, Ernest Dietzmann and Jerry Baker that were drug dependents and patients of Pollock's, and Arthur Lenz, a [[methamphetamine]] dealer. They intended to rob Pollock of his money, and their fingerprints matched those found at the crime scene. Michalec brought the case to the district attorney Terry McDonald, who refused to prosecute for unknown reasons, and Michalec's work was forgotten. All three suspects died free men.
In 2013, when journalist [[Hamilton Morris]] contacted McDonald, who explained he actually wasn't the district attorney at that time, Morris tried to investigate and was informed by the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] that they had destroyed and lost the records and information about who was responsible for the case.<ref name="harpersBloodSpore" />{{rp|14}}
