{{for|the 2011 documentary film|Unlawful Killing (film)}} In [[English law]], '''unlawful killing''' is a verdict that can be returned by an [[inquest (England and Wales)|inquest]] in [[England and Wales]] when someone has been killed by one or several unknown persons. The verdict means that the killing was done without lawful excuse and in breach of [[criminal law]]. This includes [[murder]], [[manslaughter]], [[infanticide]] and causing [[death by dangerous driving]]. A verdict of unlawful killing generally leads to a police investigation, with the aim of gathering sufficient evidence to identify, [[Criminal charge|charge]] and [[prosecute]] those responsible.
The inquest does not normally name any individual person as responsible.<ref name="halsbury">Lord Mackay of Clashfern (ed.) (2006) ''Halsbury's Laws of England'', 4th ed. reissue, vol.9(2), "Coroners", '''1043. Killed unlawfully'''</ref> The [[Legal burden of proof|standard of proof]] is that the unlawful killing must be beyond reasonable doubt. If this standard is not met, a verdict of [[accidental death]] or [[death by misadventure]] on the balance of probabilities may be returned.<ref name="halsbury"/>
==Notable cases== A verdict of unlawful killing was returned in the following notable cases: *Lt Col [[Rupert Thorneloe]] and Trooper Joshua Hammond, of the 2nd Royal Tank Regiment, were killed in an explosion in Helmand Province in Afghanistan on 1 July 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Steven|title=Rupert Thorneloe was unlawfully killed in Afghanistan, inquest finds|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/apr/30/rupert-thorneloe-death-afghanistan-inquest|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=The Guardian|date=30 April 2010|language=en-GB}}</ref> *[[Ian Tomlinson]], who was struck with a baton and pushed to the ground by Metropolitan Police officer Simon Harwood at the G20 protests in London on 1 April 2009.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/03/ian-tomlinson-unlawfully-killed-inquest|newspaper=The Guardian|title=Ian Tomlinson unlawfully killed, inquest finds|date=3 May 2011|accessdate=3 May 2011}}</ref> * [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] and [[Dodi Al-Fayed]], killed in a car crash on 6 September 1997. A verdict of unlawful killing was returned in a 2008 inquest in London; the [[Diana, Princess of Wales#Conspiracy theories, inquest and verdict|initial French enquiry]] in 1999 concluded the crash was caused by the driver's loss of control while drunk.<ref>{{cite news|title=Princess Diana unlawfully killed|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7328754.stm|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=BBC|date=7 April 2008}}</ref> * Trooper [[190th Fighter Squadron, Blues and Royals friendly fire incident|Matty Hull]], killed in a US [[friendly fire]] incident in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6456191.stm| work=BBC News|title=Search for truth on 'friendly fire' death|date=16 March 2007|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> * [[Terry Lloyd]], ITN journalist, who was fired on by United States [[tanks]] near [[Basra]] on 22 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6046950.stm|publisher=BBC News | title=Iraq reporter unlawfully killed|date=13 October 2006| accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> * [[Iain Hook]], [[UNRWA]] worker, shot by an Israeli [[sniper]] in [[Jenin]] in 2002.<ref name=BBC2005>{{cite news|title=British UN worker unlawfully shot|newspaper=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/suffolk/4534620.stm|accessdate=13 December 2008|date=16 December 2005}}</ref> * [[Tom Hurndall]], shot by an Israeli [[sniper]] in the [[Gaza Strip]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4896800.stm|publisher=BBC News|title='Unlawful killing' of Gaza Briton|date=10 April 2006|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> * The fifty-two victims of the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]] were declared on 6 May 2011 to have been unlawfully killed.<ref>{{ cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13308371|publisher=BBC|title=7/7 inquests: Emergency delays 'did not cause deaths'|date=6 May 2011|accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref> * [[Ronald Maddison]], an airman who died whilst acting as an experimental subject in chemical weapons testing in 1953. A verdict of unlawful killing was returned in a 2004 inquest; the original 1953 inquest had returned a verdict of misadventure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nerve gas death was 'unlawful'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wiltshire/4013767.stm|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=BBC|date=15 November 2004}}</ref> * David Gray, a patient in his home in Cambridgeshire, was unlawfully killed by lethal injection administered by out-of-hours locum doctor Daniel Ubani on February 16, 2008.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2010/feb/04/doctor-daniel-ubani-unlawfully-killed-patient|publisher=Guardian newspaper|title='Doctor Daniel Ubani unlawfully killed overdose patient'|accessdate=4 Feb 2010}}</ref> *The death of 96 [[Liverpool F.C.]] fans in the [[Hillsborough disaster]] on 15 April 1989, with the ruling returned at a second inquest in April 2016: [[Hillsborough disaster#First hearing|A previous inquest]] in 1991 had returned a verdict of [[accidental death]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough inquests: Fans unlawfully killed, jury concludes|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-36138337|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=BBC News|date=27 April 2016}}</ref>
